The set of "external" bindings is divided into two datasets - the set of input bindings will utilise the inputs dataset, and the output bindings will result in an the output dataset (also known as the simulation result). Some of the input bindings will be described in the resolution of the scientificDescription, theseare the inputDescription to the simulation.
Note that the inherited OM_Observation will make a link from M4A_Simulation to the phonomena that it are simulated (observed).
This is the subset of bindings that have been exposed by the scientific description, and that will be used for discovery.

Where present, a conformance is used to indicate how a simulation conformed to a specific numerical requirement.
The value of associatedWith should correspond to the top level numerical requirement within the experiment.
The value of setMember, if present, should indicate the correspondence to a specific member of a requirementSet.
Where a conformance is to a numerical requirement which has options, one optionChoice number should be provided, corresponding to the selected option.
The deliveredBy attribute should identify how the base simulation has been modified (if it was modified) to correspond to this requirement.
Note that the inherited OM_Observation will make a link from M4A_Simulation to the phonomena that it are simulated (observed).

This set of bindings is the actual real bindings that are necessary to run the model. They may or may not be recorded for later use.

These are used for making runtime modifications to a configured model.
Note that the common use of namelists to provide runtime configuration should be handled by describing the default namelist options in the configured model description, and the runtime specific changes using this method.

Need to constrian the descriptions to be unconfigured.

A process describes a specific real world process.
A process may have sub components: e.g. atmosphere, and ocean, and there is at the process level a one-to-one mapping between the scientific and software descriptions.
These mappings go down the hierarchy until such time as the underlying mappings are no longer one to one, in which case the composition relationships are independently described within the scientific description and the software description component hierarchies.
In practice then, a process must have a scientific description, if it doesn't then any detail is handled in the software description.
Other possible names component, software, process, physicalprocessorfeatureofatmosphere,scheme etc.

Where a configuration change has resulted in a change in a specific description (the target), and the changed value can be reflected using the description mechanism, it shoudl be recorded as a resultsIn description.
Consumers of the M4A_Observation should then discard the target description and replace it with the resultsIn description.
This could include namellists and compile ttime choices. These are time indepenent.
Normally used as a bug fix. This should be used when the code has been changed, but there is no consequential change to the descriptions.
These modifications are applied directly to the code, and are not able to be reflected in a configuration change (the variable is not described in any of the available descriptions).
Lays out the relationship between processes, scientific descriptions, and software descriptions.
